{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_geranium_ver02/data/sn84028102/00340580813/1957122601/0810.xml":{"full_text":"Christ\n4\u2014THE RECORD, CHARDON, OHIO, DEC. 26, 1957\nMerry Christmas.\nGEAUGA RECORD\nServing Geauga County Folk Since 1849\nPublished Every Thursday at Chardon, Ohio\nOwned and Published by Geauga Publishers, Inc.\nJOHN GORE, Managing Editor\nTERRY PERKINS, Editor\nMerry Christmas\nwill be born again in Geauga county this week,\ncome again into our lives more fully in many\nwill come to the woman working at her stove\nChrist will\nways. He\npreparing Christmas dinner. He will comd into the eyes of\nfathers as they watch their children playing near the\nChristmas tree. He will come to children as they realize\na little the love and care that protects them.\n*The bustle and hustle of this world seems to reach a\ncrescendo at the Christmas season. The spirit of Christmas\nand the birth of the Christ child seems sometimes forgotten\na hustling, busy\nof quietness for\nin the rush. It is not so. The world is\nplace, but it takes only a few moments\nChrist to reach you.\nYou can help. You can give a little\nChristmas this week with every Christmas present and card.\nYou can continue to give it to those you come in contact\nwith every day of the year.\nAnd if you in turn will receive the finest gift of all\u2014\na richer, more significant, a more valuable life of your own.\nLighter than leather! \u2022Lighter than rubber!\nLet us rebuild your shoes with\nWe\u2019Carry Shoes for the Whole Family\nP. DeGeorge Shoe Store\nGood Quality Good Banrains\nNext to the Geauga Theatre\nOur thanks and best wishes for a Happy\nHoliday to all of you whom it has been our\ngreat privilege and pleasure to know and to serve.\nYour Geauga County\nWelcome Wagon Hostesses\nSubscribe to the Geauga Record\nMcBRIDE BROTHERS\nCHARDON, OHIO\nof the spirit of\nJohn\nmicrolite\nFULL HALF\nSOLES\nYour Cat\u2019s Paw Shoe Repairer\nWe join with Santa\nin wishing you a joyous\nYuletide season and the\nvery best of everything!\nincluding township trustees and\nconstables, village and school\nboard officials.\nThe Montville Grange held\nrites at the grave as the deceas\ned had been a member of this\nGrange for nearly 50 years. Bur\nial was made in the Montville\nCemetery. Much sympathy is ex\ntended to the bereaved family.\nFriends and relatives from\nCleveland, Cleveland Heights,\nMiddlefield, Windsor, Austin\nburg, Jefferson, Chardon, and\nMontville attended the funeral.\nMrs. Mildred Wenzel and\ndaughter, Margaret, called on\nMr. and Mrs. William McLaugh\nlin in Burton Thursday evening.\nMr. and Mrs. Leonard Geis\nman are spending a\nin North Carolina.\nEDITOR ON MAIN STREET\nSEASONAL STUFF: If I were\nSanta Claus,\nI\u2019d appoint myself Geauga\nCounty Welfare Director. St.\nNick\u2019s had years of experience\nin Welfare work.\nI\u2019d give Geauga County a new\njail, large enough to adequately\nserve the county, and in a cen\ntral location so the sheriff\u2019s de\npartment could provide protec\ntion, more equally, to all parts\nof the county.\ni I\u2019d give gold medals to all of\nGeauga\u2019s citizens who were\nelected to the low-salary, high\ncomplaint\noffices In November,\nI\u2019d provide enough funds for\nresearch to determine, once and\nfor all, whether the Geaugans\nwho claim they saw flying sau\ncers really did, or if they need\nan eye examination.\nI\u2019d give Chardon Plaza pro-\nMontville Funeral Rites\nHeld for Leroy Wenzel\nBy MRS. MILDRED SKINNER\nPhone Montville 3484\nMONTVILLE Funeral ser\nvices were held Wednesday af\nternoon at the Burr Funeral\nHome in Chardon for Leroy\nWenzel who had been a Mont\nville resident for 63 years. Rev.\nLewis of the Methodist Episco\nlai Church here and Rev. Gar\nlich of the Huntsburg Baptist\nChurch officiated. Mr. Wenzel\nhas been affiliated with the\nMontville churches. Pallbearers\nwere Charles Leggett, Louis\nBurger, Fred Hoffman, Robert\nScheller, William Leslein, and\nAlbert Rabatin, all members of\nthe Montville Volunteer Fire De\npartment of which Mr. Wenzel\nwas a member.\nfew days\nis confin\nillness.\nMr. Floyd Hoffman\ned to his home with\nGene Wright, son of Mr. and\nMrs. Eugene Wright had the\nmisfortune to break his arm re\ncently.\nA Christmas program was pre\nsented by the school children at\nthe school Tuesday evening a\nvery large crowd attended. Re\nfreshments were served by the\nPTC ladies.\nIN SERVICE\nPACIFIC FLEET Roger O.\nCarter, seaman apprentice,\nUSN, son of Mrs. Dolly I. Nash\nof 38 Gorder Dr., Chardon, is\nserving aboard the heavy cruis\ner USS Bremerton now under\ngoing refresher training off the\ncoast of California.\nThe Bremerton com 1 e e\nnearly four-months of overhaul\nand repairs in the Puget Sound\nNaval Shipyard in Bremerton,\nWash., early in November.\nThe cruiser\u2019s homeport is\nLong Beach, Calif.\n\u201cPHIL\u2019\nmoters and merchants a pat on\nthe back for providing Chardon\narea shoppers with a bigger se\nlection of merchandise than ev\ner before, and I\u2019d give Main St.\nmerchants an equal pat for\nmeeting the new competition\nvigorously. All of it makes this\ncommunity a better place in\nwhich to live.\nI\u2019d eliminate all automobile\naccidents, especially those over\nthe holidays.\nI\u2019d bring more big industry to\nGeauga County to help foot the\never increasing tax bill now\ndrawing too much from the poc\nkets of county home owners.\nI\u2019d provide every school in the\ncounty with enough classrooms\nto meet its needs for the next\nhalf century.\nREFLECTIONS after walking\ndown Euclid Ave. during the\nChristmas season, with apolo\ngies to Joyce Kilmer:\nI\u2019M DREAMING of a white\nChristmas may be Geauga Coun\nty\u2019s theme song tomorrow, un\nless the weather changes be\ntween now and then. Whethe\nit\u2019s white or greenv all of us at\nthe newspaper extend our best\nwishes for a happy holiday sea\nson. tp\nAn exchange of gifts was held\nin each class room of the school\nFriday afternoon with Santa pre\nsent. Scholars are now enjoying\na two weeks vacation.\nScholars attending Thompson\nHigh School enjoyed an ex\nchange of gifts in the homeroom\nand a Christmas party for FHA\ngirls Thursday.\nMr. Myron Sober is slowly re\ncovering from a serious illness.\nTitle Company\nNames Thrasher\nAssistant Veep\nhad\nwith\nwas\nMrs. Robert Davidson\nbeen confined to her home\nillness several days and\ntaken to the Painesville hospit\nal by the Firemens Emergency\ncar last Monday afternoon. She\nis being treated there for virus\npneumonia.\nwishes you and yours\nthe very best for a\nA Very Merry Christmas\nand a Happy and Prosperous\nNew Year!\nThanks again for your help and support this past year\nPHIL ADAMS\nNew York Life Insurance Co.\nBox 74 East Claridon, Ohio\nPhone E. Claridon 6-6916\nI\nI will never see,\npurple Christmas\nI hope that\nAnother\ntree.\nA tree some\nwith paint\nTo make it\nain\u2019t\nA tree that\nto make\nA garish, ugly nature fake.\nEven bad verse by fools like\nme\nIs better than a purple tree.\nhas sprayed\ngoon\nlook like that it\nwould blush\nGod\nThrasher is Manager of the O\nGeauga County Office of The\nCuyahoga Abstract Title and\nTurst Company which is locat\ned at 201 E. Main Street in Char\ndon.\nThrasher has been associated\nwith Cuyahoga since June of\n1946 working as a Title Examin\ner until April of 1955 when he\nwas elected Assistant Secretary\nand mad Assistant Manger of\nthe Chardon branch. Thrasher\nhs been branch manager since\nAugust of 1956. He is married,\nhas two children and resides at\n330 Downing Drive in Chardon.\n1 \u2014a\nA tree, the small fry, and Christmas morning\u2014u sure-fire snapshot\ncombination.\nP!an to Shoot a Christmas Story\nToday we\u2019d like to tell you how\none family we\u2019ve heard about re\ncords Christmas at their house.\nA week or so before the holi\nday, all the members sit down for\na \u201cstory conference.\u201d Everybody\nmakes suggestions about what\nshould be included as picture ma\nterial, and a list of all the mutual\nly-agreed-upon items is drawn up.\nThis \u201cshooting list\u201d generally\ncontains such preliminary activi\nties as Junior\u2019s letter to Santa\nmaking and decorating Christmas\ncookies putting the traditional\ntrimmings on doorways and fire\nplace festive store windows and\nfat Santas packages and mail\nbringing home the tree and decor\nating it hanging the children\u2019s\nstockings carolers on Christmas\nEve, etc. For Christmas Day itself,\nhigh on the list come gift-open\ning, holiday callers, test runs of\nskates and bicycles, and, of course,\nChristmas dinner.\nAs you can see, the story begins\nto take shape. The first shot will\nprobably be Junior peering into\na store window\u2014then a close-up\nKronk-Peck\nto 'Marry\nSaturday\nOpen church will be observed\nat the wedding of Iona Jean\nPeck to Kenneth Carl Kronk on\nDec. 28 at 3:30 p.m., at the Char\ndon Methodist Church.\nParties' honoring Miss Peck in\nthe, past few weeks are the fol\nlowing:\nMrs. Lloyd Johnson entertain\ned at her home on Baldwin Rd.,\nwith a linen shower, on Fri. ev\nening, Nov. 2.\nMrs. Damian Tagum had a\nsurprise get acquantied party\nfor her sister, having the Peck\nKronk relatives, Sunday after\nnoon, Nov. 17, at the Livingston\nMather Estate. Twenty-six were\npresent. Iona received many\nlovely miscellaneous gifts. Mrs.\nEdward Welch and Mrs. Lloyd\nJohnson assisted Mrs. Tagum in\nserving a buffet supper.\nSara Jane Cartwright, Lois\nBrittan and Carol Dalenburg en\ntertained 15 guests on Wednes\nday evening Dec. 4, at their a\npartment on Buckeye Rd. with\na personal shower.\nWILLMAN J. THRASHER\nWillman J. Thrasher has been\nelected assistant vice president\nof The Cuyahoga Abstract Title\nand Trust Company, it was an-t\nnounced yesterdy by Peter D. i\nKleist, Chirman of the Board,\nand Laurence Ptak Presl- J/FWPftf/\n(^ondUCtS AmiUal,\nChristmas Party\nGeauga V.F.W. Post 6519 and\nauxiliary held their annual\nChristmas party at the Post\nClub rooms Dec. 15. A planned\npot-luck supper was served at\n5:30 to approximately 30 fami\nlies. Mrs. Howard Richards,\nwife of the Post Commander\ngave the welcome. Mrs. Ger\ntrude Parsons, Auxilliary Chap\nlain, gave the devotionals. A pic\nture show was enjoyed, after\nwhich Santa distributed gifts\nthe children.\nThrasher was active in Civic\nAffairs having served as a coun\ncilman of the Village of Char\ndon. In addition to being Chair\nman of the Planning Commis\nsion, he is a member of the\nZoning Appeals Board in Char\ndon, The Rotary, Geauga Coun\nty Real Estate Board, Cleve-. iire\nland Real Estate Board Heights Auxilliary was held Dec. 19 at\nRound Table and the Southeast home Of Loretta Mae Hol\nRound Table.| mes ten members present enjoy-\nto\nat\non\nLake County Council met\nthe home of Loretta Holmes\nDec. 17.\nThe regular meeting of the\ned a gift exchange. Cards were\n1 signed for our out of state and\nI ill members. Refreshments were\nserved by Mrs. Holmes and Le\nonarda Wells.\nThere will be no meeting on\nJan. second. Next meeting Jan.\n16 at the home of Attie and Wil\nma Holmes.\nPostpone Meetings\nof Chardon Boards\nBecause the regular meeting\nnight of the Chardon Cemetery\nBoard and the Board of Public\nAffairs falls this year on New\nYear\u2019s Day, these meetings\nhave been postponed, according\nto village clerk Jennie C. David\nson.\nThe Board of Public Affairs\nwill meet on Friday evening,\nJan. 3, and the Cemetery Board\non Wednesday evening, Jan. 8.\nQuM\ni\nof one particular toy. From then\nop, the toy becomes the unifying\ntheme that holds the story to\ngether\u2014whether it\u2019s to be record\ned on snapshot film or by a movie\ncamera. Junior confers with a\ncurbstone Santa he writes a let\nter to Santa.\nThen, a series of shots will\nshow trimming the tree\u2014until\nthe Star of Bethlehem at last\nshines forth from the very top.\nThe gifts\u2014including the toy\u2014are\nwrapped and piled high at the\nfoot of the tree\u2014and the stock\nings are \u201chung with care\u201d at the\nfireplace.\nOn Christmas morning, Junior\nopens his gifts\u2014and \u201cBoy meets\ntoy\u201d. A good close-up shot of his\nreaction will almost tell a story\nall by itself\u2014and so will the faces\nof the holiday callers to whom\nhe shows off his new and already\nbeloved toy. Don\u2019t even be sur\nprised to see the toy going along\nto the dinner table\u2014and finally\nto bed with him after a wonder\nfully exciting day!\n\u2014John Van Guilder\nTawankas Give\nTelevision Set\nto County Home\nMembers of Chardon\u2019s Ta\nwanka Club wished residents at\nthe county home a merry Christ\nmas by presenting them with a\n21-inch television set Sunday af\nternoon. The goup sang carols\nwhen the set was given.\nIn addition to the television\nset the group also gave two com\nplete Christmas dinner baskets\nto deserving families, according\nto Mrs. Marlene Taylor, publi\ncity chiarman. The Christmas\nprojects were headed by Mrs.\nAnnette Medina.\nOn Dec. 19, at the home of\nMrs. Bonnie Leyde, the group\nheld its Christmas party with a\ngift exchange and carol sing.\nClub business was taken care of\nat the start of the party. Mrs.\nLeyde served refreshments.\nKiwanis to Sponsor\nDinner for Students\nA party for all Geauga County\nWe have a long,\nlong list of warm wishes\nfor all our friends for a\nbright and joyous holiday!\nKing\u2019s\nCENTRAL STORE\n141 Main St.\nChardon\nRelease Figures on Geauga\u2019s \u201857 Business\nThe first facts and figures re\nvealing the amount of retail bus\niness done in Geauga County up\nto the middle of this year have\njust been released.\nThey show* that outlays for\nconsumer goods were high, al\nthough a certain part of each\ndollar so spent represented an\nincrease in prices. Incomes,\nwhich made possible the large\nscale buying, were at a new\npeak.\nThe survey, covering every\npart of the United States, is for\nthe twelve months ending July\n1, 1957. It was produced by the\nStandard Rate and Data Ser\nvice based on data gathered\nfrom national, state and local\nsources.\nGeauga County residents, it\nreveals, had more money to\nspend, after payment of taxes,\ni than they did in the prior year.\nLocal incomes reached $59,560,\n000 net, compared with $55,203,\n000, previously.\nPer family, determined by di\nviding this amount by the esti\nmated 9,570 local families, there\nwsas a spendable income of $6,\n224.\nThis compares favorably with\nthe $5,931 per family average in\nthe United States.\nA large part of this income\nwent into consumer goods pur\nchases in the local retail stores.\nThe public generally, confi-|\ndent that there would be no in\nterruption in the steady good\nI times, continued to spend free\nly. In so doing, according to\nleading economists, they uncon\nsciously bolstered the economy,\nwhich was showing signs of hes\nitancy at that time. The business\ndip, therefore, did not material\nize until a little later.\nLocally, this confident spend-\ning mood produced a gross re-\ncollege students and service\nmen, sponsored by the Kiwanis\nwith the Key Clubs of Geauga\nI County acting as hosts, will be\nI held Thursday, according to Dr.\nW. C. Corey, chairman of the\nentertainment committee.\ni The dinner will be held at the\nManor house at underson\n'starting at 7 p.m. and admis\nsion will be free.\nFor the Best in\nHEATING\nfirst line by\nJ. P. WALSH\nand Sons\nChardon 6-1691\nBeer Wine\nChampagne\nVermouth\nCordials\nEgg Nog\nRock Rye\nDecanters\nMiniatures\nGift Boxes\nand Baskets\nMixers Beverages\nHome Bar Supplies\nGlassware\nMixing Sets\nand Novelties\nCHARDON\nBEVERAGE\nGeauga County's\nLargest Beverage Store\nNext to Ice House\nWater St. Chardon 5-5661\nPLUMBING\nHot Water Heating\nElectrical\nWater Heaters\nElectrical Contracting\n\u2022Goulds Water Pumps\nForrest 0. Greene\nRD 1, Chardon Ph. 5-9128\nANNOUNCING\ntail volume of $28,231,000 in the\nyear. This compares with $27,\n899,000 in the prior twelve\nmonths.\nNearly every kind of retail en\nterprise was able to show a gain,\nthe automotive business being\nan important exception.\nThe slowdown that has occurr\ned since then is expected by\nmost experts to be moderate.\nThey say it will extend into mid\n1958, when a gradual recovery\nwill begin.\nAs one of them points out, in\nU.S. Newis and World Report,\n\u201cpeople need to go on eating\nand wearing clothes and travel\ning and paying rent and repair\nbills. And a year from now there\nwill be three million more of\nthem.\u201d _____\nWatch and Jewelry\nRepair\u2014Expert Service\nDAVID WILLSON\nALBERTS Jewelry\nChardon\nIn Chardon it\u2019s\nfinch\nCleaners Dyers\nINC.\nfor ALL Your\nDr/ Cleaning Needs!\nCall for pick-up and\nDelivery Service\n518 Water St.\nPhone 5'2135\nFuel Oil\nHeating\nw\nw\nMobil heat\nSOCON* MOBIL HEATING OIL\nCHARDON OIL\nCOMPANY\nTelephone Chardon 5-7711\nYOU CAN OWN\na\nMcCulloch\nMAC-35 CHAIN SAW\n$181.00\nWith 20\u201d Blade and Chain\nSee Us for A\nDEMONSTRATION\nRebuilt\nand\nGuaranteed\nUsed\nChain Saws\nDiedrich Co.\nROUTE 44 South CHARDON\nTelephone 5-8661\nrances\nof our staff\nformerly with Halle's is now a member\nHairstylist\nFor Appointment Call Chardon 6-2811\nJAMES DALE\nCHARDON SHOPPING PLAZA\nOpen Monday thru Saturday, 9 to 6\nThursday and Friday until 9\nAIR CONDITIONED","height":"28236","width":"21660"}}
